Data Wrangling Practice

Joe Eldredge | jwe2n@virginia.edu

Purpose of Exercise

In this exercise I go over some of the fundamental commands from tidyverse library that I use all the time to tidy datasets or wrangle. You can see variants of this used in pretty much every work on my portfolio. The example comes from Mike Chappeles Data Wrangling in R LinkedIn course.

The first is just regarding reading in datasets.

Transforming from Wide to Long Dataset

We are going to transform the coal tibble using gather, which gathers columns into key-value pairs:

#> Rows: 6,960
#> Columns: 3
#> $ region           <chr> "North America", "Bermuda", "Canada", "Greenland", "
#> $ year             <chr> "1980", "1980", "1980", "1980", "1980", "1980", "198
#> $ coal_consumption <chr> "16.45179", "0", "0.96156", "0.00005", "0.10239", "0

Now I need to transform the year to an integer, as I can see from above it is a character.

coal_long$year <- as.integer(coal_long$year)
coal_long$coal_consumption <- as.numeric(coal_long$coal_consumption)
summary(coal_long)

I notice using the unique command that there are some values in region that I dont want because they are not countries. It is generally important not to have distinctly different data within the same column. I will put them in their own tibble for now. The not (!) operator at the beginning of the last statement inverts the results of is.na to show where I had not nas meaning where I had non-continents.
